ves into a new middle-class caste in India, the United States, and elsewhere. Fuller and Narasimhan offer one of the most comprehensive looks at Tamil Brahmans around the world to date. They examine Brahman migration from rural to urban areas, more recent transnational migration, and how the Brahman way of life has translated to both Indian cities and American suburbs. They look at modern education and the new employment opportunities afforded by engineering and IT. They examine how Sanskritic Hinduism and traditional music and dance have shaped Tamil Brahmans’ particular middle-class sensibilities and how middle-class status is related to the changing position of women. Above all, they explore the complex relationship between class and caste systems and the ways in which hierarchy has persisted in modernized India.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aBrahmansxSocial conditionsxIndiaxTamil Nadu. 0aBrahmansxSocial conditions. 0aBrahmanszIndiazTamil NaduxSocial conditions. 0aCastexIndiaxTamil Nadu. 0aCastezIndiaxTamil Nadu. 0aCastezIndiazTamil Nadu. 0aCaste. 0aMiddle classxIndiaxTamil Nadu. 0aMiddle classzIndiazTamil Nadu. 0aMiddle class. 0aSocial history. 0aTamil (Indic people)xSocial conditionsxIndiaxTamil Nadu. 0aTamil (Indic people)xSocial conditions. 0aTamil (Indic people)zIndiazTamil NaduxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aNarasimhan, Haripriya, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226152882423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226152882.jpg  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-de